 territorial expansion and relations with native peoples; immigration and voting rights. But the key lies in the evolution and enforcement of jurisdictional law, which illuminates the way social relations and state power developed in the two countries. Written in an accessible and engaging style, this book will appeal to readers of sociology, politics, law, and history as well as to anyone interested in the relationship between the United States and Canada.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 0aJurisdictionzCanadaxHistory. 0aJurisdictionzUnited StatesxHistory. 0aNational characteristics, American. 0aNational characteristics, Canadian. 0aPolitical culturezCanada. 0aPolitical culturezUnited States. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / History & Theory.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/9780674274457zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674274457423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780674274457/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK